31. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D06FFE2FF8DFF0AFD3EBB17BAE8" authority="Barneby" authorityName="Barneby" box="[178,513,736,763]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="orbignyana">
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFF0AFD3EB88CBAE8" bold="true" box="[178,410,736,763]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Mimosa orbignyana</emphasis>
Barneby
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C357650EFFE2FF8DFF30FCDBBADDBDB4" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BF23685FFE2FF8DFF30FCDBBADDBDB4" blockId="15.[136,1452,736,1447]" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">
This species has remained poorly understood, known only from the 
<typeStatus id="54F68827FFE2FF8DFCD1FCDBBA8FBB0C" box="[873,921,773,799]" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">type</typeStatus>
collection (
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFBA2FCDABDABBB0C" box="[1050,1213,772,799]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">díOrbigny 743</emphasis>
P, 
<collectingCountry id="F35A7615FFE2FF8DFB61FCDBBC38BB0C" box="[1241,1326,773,799]" name="Bolivia" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, Chiquitos, 
<date id="FFF31045FFE2FF8DFF30FCF7B80ABB50" box="[136,284,809,835]" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" value="1831-08">August 1831</date>
), and apparently never re-collected since, until very recently. It was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDC4B74FFE2FF8DFB0DFCF7BC73BB50" author="Barneby, R. C." box="[1205,1381,809,835]" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" pagination="1 - 835" part="65" refString="Barneby, R. C. (1991) Sensitivae Censitae: a description of the genus Mimosa L. (Mimosaceae) in the New World. Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden 65: 1 - 835." title="Sensitivae Censitae: a description of the genus Mimosa L. (Mimosaceae) in the New World" type="journal article" year="1991">Barneby (1991)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFA34FCF7B8F2BB99" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">
‘in unknown habitat, but to be sought in campo or cerrado at or above 
<quantity id="4CB59B60FFE2FF8DFCC1FC93BAA8BB75" box="[889,958,845,871]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" unit="m" value="700.0">700 m</quantity>
on the Sierra de Santiago, near 
<geoCoordinate id="EE795042FFE2FF8DFA90FC93BC99BB74" box="[1320,1423,845,871]" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" precision="925" value="-18.5">18° 30´S</geoCoordinate>
in south-east 
<collectingRegion id="4989F867FFE2FF8DFEB9FCAFB896BB98" box="[257,384,881,907]" country="Bolivia" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
, Boliviaí
</emphasis>
and has been considered endemic to 
<collectingCountry id="F35A7615FFE2FF8DFCC5FCAFBAD9BB98" box="[893,975,881,907]" name="Bolivia" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
. Within the last two years, two collections, both from further north, on the Serranía Huanchaca have been made (
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFC0CFC4BBD9EBBBD" box="[948,1160,916,942]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">J.R.I. Wood 26772</emphasis>
, 
<collectionCode id="ED5CAE40FFE2FF8DFB21FC4BBDD9BBBC" box="[1177,1231,917,943]" country="Bolivia" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15532" name="Herbario Nacional de Bolivia, Universidad Mayor de San Andr�s" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">LPB</collectionCode>
, K, 
<collectionCode id="ED5CAE40FFE2FF8DFABBFC4BBC2DBBBC" box="[1283,1339,917,943]" country="Bolivia" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15753" name="Museo de Historia Natural Noel Kempff Mercado -- Universidad Aut�noma Gabriel Ren� Moreno" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">USZ</collectionCode>
, from the southwest part of the meseta of the Serranía Huanchaca in the Noel Kempf National Park in 
<collectingCountry id="F35A7615FFE2FF8DFB13FC67BC16BBC0" box="[1195,1280,953,979]" name="Bolivia" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, and 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFA86FC67B9A4BBE4" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">L. Borges 787</emphasis>
, UB, from the southern end of the Huanchaca range in neighbouring 
<collectingRegion id="4989F867FFE2FF8DFC75FC03BD76BBE4" box="[973,1120,989,1015]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
in 
<collectingCountry id="F35A7615FFE2FF8DFB3FFC03BDD8BBE4" box="[1159,1230,989,1015]" name="Brazil" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, where the range is known as the Serra do Ricardo Franco). However, despite extensive fieldwork in areas where d’Orbigny is likely to have visited in ‘Chiquitos’, no material matching this species has been re-collected from any of these areas. This is perhaps surprising, given that 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D06FFE2FF8DFE66FB97BB90BC71" box="[478,646,1096,1122]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="orbignyana">
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFE66FB97BB90BC71" box="[478,646,1096,1122]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. orbignyana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms a substantial shrub to 
<quantity id="4CB59B60FFE2FF8DFC77FB97BAEABC70" box="[975,1020,1097,1123]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" unit="m" value="2.0">2 m</quantity>
height, multi-stemmed from the base, resprouting after fire from an underground woody root system that is much thicker than the above-ground stems, and with conspicuous 
<quantity id="4CB59B60FFE2FF8DFEEAFB4FB8B8BCB8" box="[338,430,1169,1195]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" unit="m" value="1.1" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="1.0">1–1.2 m</quantity>
tall efoliate pseudoracemes of bright pink flowers (
<figureCitation id="13762A00FFE2FF8DFC48FB4FBD2BBCB8" box="[1008,1085,1169,1195]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="16.[136,229,2024,2046]" captionTargetBox="[234,1362,209,1978]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[189,1398,190,1997]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 6. Mimosa orbignyana. A. Habit and flowering shoots; B. Stipules; C. Leaflets; D. Floral bracts; E. Flower; F. Longitudinal section of flower, all from J. R. I. Wood et al. 26772 (LPB, K). Drawn by Rosemary Wise." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/192181/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation id="13762A00FFE2FF8DFBD9FB4FBD67BCB8" box="[1121,1137,1169,1195]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="17.[136,229,949,971]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,923]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,190,923]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 7. Mimosa orbignyana. A. Habit; B. habitat; C. multiple stems from base resprouting after fire; D. leaves; E. indumentum; F. inflorescences. All from L. Borges 787 (UB), Serranía Huanchaca. Photos by Leonardo Borges." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/192182/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">7</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDC4B74FFE2FF8DFB3EFB4FBC20BCB8" author="Barneby, R. C." box="[1158,1334,1169,1195]" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" pagination="1 - 835" part="65" refString="Barneby, R. C. (1991) Sensitivae Censitae: a description of the genus Mimosa L. (Mimosaceae) in the New World. Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden 65: 1 - 835." title="Sensitivae Censitae: a description of the genus Mimosa L. (Mimosaceae) in the New World" type="journal article" year="1991">Barneby (1991)</bibRefCitation>
placed 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D06FFE2FF8DFA35FB4FB81FBCDD" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="orbignyana">
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFA35FB4FB81FBCDD" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. orbignyana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in his ser. 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFE3AFB6BB8CEBCDC" box="[386,472,1205,1231]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Setosae</emphasis>
of sect. 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFD8EFB6ABBB5BCDD" box="[566,675,1204,1230]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Habbasia</emphasis>
and indicated likely affinities to 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFBADFB6BBD9DBCDD" box="[1045,1163,1204,1230]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. riedelii</emphasis>
Benth. from the Chapada dos Guimar„es in 
<collectingRegion id="4989F867FFE2FF8DFEE4FB07B8E6BCE0" box="[348,496,1241,1267]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
and 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFD94FB07BBAABCE1" box="[556,700,1241,1266]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. aguapeia</emphasis>
Barneby from the Serra do Aguapei also in 
<collectingRegion id="4989F867FFE2FF8DFB7CFB07BC4ABCE0" box="[1220,1372,1241,1267]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
. These overall affinities are confirmed by analysis of a 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFD1DFB23BA05BD05" box="[677,787,1277,1303]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">trnD -trnT</emphasis>
sequence of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D06FFE2FF8DFC11FB23BD46BD05" box="[937,1104,1276,1302]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="orbignyana">
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFC11FB23BD46BD05" box="[937,1104,1276,1302]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. orbignyana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as sister to a clade comprising ser. 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFF0CFAFFB81CBD28" box="[180,266,1313,1339]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Setosae</emphasis>
and ser. 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFED2FAFEB8E8BD29" box="[362,510,1312,1338]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Pachycarpae</emphasis>
(clade O in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDC4B74FFE2FF8DFD3CFAFFBA47BD28" author="Dahmer, N. &amp; Simon, M. F. &amp; Schifino-Wittmann, M. T. &amp; Hughes, C. E. &amp; Miotto, S. T. S. &amp; Giuliani, J. C." box="[644,849,1312,1339]" journalOrPublisher="Plant Systematics &amp; Evolution" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" pagination="211 - 220" part="291" publicationUrl="http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s00606-010-0382-2" refString="Dahmer, N., Simon, M. F., Schifino-Wittmann, M. T., Hughes, C. E., Miotto, S. T. S. &amp; Giuliani, J. C. (2011) Chromosome numbers in the genus Mimosa L.: cytotaxonomic and evolutionary implications. Plant Systematics &amp; Evolution 291: 211 - 220. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00606 - 010 - 0382 - 2" title="Chromosome numbers in the genus Mimosa L.: cytotaxonomic and evolutionary implications" type="journal article" year="2011">
Simon 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFD6CFAFFBA12BD29" box="[724,772,1312,1338]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">et al</emphasis>
. (2011
</bibRefCitation>
)) plus 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFC26FAFFBD59BD29" box="[926,1103,1312,1338]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. corynadenia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13762A00FFE2FF8DFBE5FAFFBD8BBD28" box="[1117,1181,1313,1339]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1920,1942]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,198,1871]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,190,1893]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Chloroplast phylogeny of Mimosa. A. 50 % majority-rule consensus tree based on Bayesian analysis of 382 trnD - trnT noncoding plastid sequences. Numbers above branches are posterior probability values. The major clades proposed by Simon et al. (2011) are indicated with letters and sizes are proportional to the number of accessions included. B. Detail of clades containing new species here described from Bolivia and other newly generated sequences of species of doubtful identity are highlighted in grey." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/192176/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Although no sequence data are available yet for 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFE09FA9BBB3CBD4D" box="[433,554,1348,1374]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. riedelii</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFDDEFA9BBBE0BD4D" box="[614,758,1349,1374]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. aguapeia</emphasis>
, the discovery of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D06FFE2FF8DFC72FA9BBD65BD4D" box="[970,1139,1348,1374]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="orbignyana">
<emphasis id="B939EA97FFE2FF8DFC72FA9BBD65BD4D" box="[970,1139,1348,1374]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. orbignyana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Serranía Huanchaca confirms Barneby’s notion that these three potentially closely allied species occupy disjunct ranges on these ancient sandstone chapadas around the periphery of the upper Rio 
<collectingCountry id="F35A7615FFE2FF8DFCA1FA53BA97BDB4" box="[793,897,1421,1447]" name="Paraguay" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">
<collectingRegion id="4989F867FFE2FF8DFCA1FA53BA97BDB4" box="[793,897,1421,1447]" country="Paraguay" name="Asuncion" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Paraguay</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
basin.
</paragraph>
